TITLE: Iterating and modifying a vector using iter_mut() in Rust
DESCRIPTION: This snippet demonstrates how to use iter_mut() to iterate over and modify a vector in Rust. It mutably borrows each element, allowing in-place modification of the collection. The example shows how to change vector elements based on a match condition.
SOURCE: https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-by-example.git/blob/master/src/flow_control/for.md#2025-04-21_snippet_4

LANGUAGE: rust
CODE:
```
fn main() {
    let mut names = vec!["Bob", "Frank", "Ferris"];

    for name in names.iter_mut() {
        *name = match name {
            &mut "Ferris" => "There is a rustacean among us!",
            _ => "Hello",
        }
    }

    println!("names: {:?}", names);
}
```

